id isPermaLink="true">https://blog.shaishav.kr/2024/08/14/tech-tip---my-wsl2-devsetup-for-terminal-productivity/</guid> <enclosure url="https://blog.shaishav.kr/assets/images/social/Articles/2024/Aug/My-WSL2-devsetup-for-terminal-productivity.png" type="image/png" length="62228" /> </item> <item> <title>Tech Tip - Make Neovim Python LSP play nice with pyenv</title> <category>Engineering</category> <category>topic/devtools</category> <category>topic/engineering</category> <category>topic/neovim</category> <category>topic/python</category> <description>Modern python development relies on some form of virtual environment management. pyenv + virtialenv is a goto toolkit for managing both python versions and isolated package environments. For people using Neovim as their editor, setting up Neovim&#39;s LSP to play nice with pyenv requires a trick. This post covers the interplay of tools to make this work.</description><link>https://blog.shaishav.kr/2024/07/26/tech-tip---make-neovim-python-lsp-play-nice-with-pyenv/?utm_source=documentation&amp;utm_medium=RSS&amp;utm_campaign=feed-syndication</link> <pubDate>Fri, 26 Jul 2024 07:41:58 +0000</pubDate><source url="https://blog.shaishav.kr/feed_rss_created.xml">wiresurfer's library | © shaishav.kr</source><guid isPermaLink="true">https://blog.shaishav.kr/2024/07/26/tech-tip---make-neovim-python-lsp-play-nice-with-pyenv/</guid> <enclosure url="https://blog.shaishav.kr/assets/images/social/Articles/2024/July/Tech Tip - Make Neovim Python LSP play nice with pyenv.png" type="image/png" length="62981" /> </item> <item> <title>Home</title> <description></description><link>https://blog.shaishav.kr/?utm_source=documentation&amp;utm_medium=RSS&amp;utm_campaign=feed-syndication</link> <pubDate>Tue, 23 Jul 2024 20:37:31 +0000</pubDate><source url="https://blog.shaishav.kr/feed_rss_created.xml">wiresurfer's library | © shaishav.kr</source><guid isPermaLink="true">https://blog.shaishav.kr/</guid> <enclosure url="https://blog.shaishav.kr/assets/images/social/index.png" type="image/png" length="34062" /> </item> <item> <title>Ghost in a shell - What the heck is a Terminal/Shell/TTY?</title> <category>Engineering</category> <category>series/bits-n-bytes</category> <category>topic/deep-dives</category> <category>topic/devops</category> <category>topic/platform-engineering</category> <description>&lt;h1&gt;Ghost in a shell - What the heck is a Terminal/Shell/TTY?&lt;/h1&gt;&lt;p&gt;Long ago, in the early days of computing, when machines were vast and mysterious entities hidden behind layers of complexity, the world of Unix was emerging. It was a time when interactions with these computing behemoths were facilitated by peculiar devices known as terminals.&lt;/p&gt;</description><link>https://blog.shaishav.kr/2024/04/07/ghost-in-a-shell---what-the-heck-is-a-terminalshelltty/?utm_source=documentation&amp;utm_medium=RSS&amp;utm_campaign=feed-syndication</link> <pubDate>Tue, 23 Jul 2024 20:37:31 +0000</pubDate><source url="https://blog.shaishav.kr/feed_rss_created.xml">wiresurfer's library | © shaishav.kr</source><guid isPermaLink="true">https://blog.shaishav.kr/2024/04/07/ghost-in-a-shell---what-the-heck-is-a-terminalshelltty/</guid> <enclosure url="https://blog.shaishav.kr/assets/images/social/Articles/2024/April/Ghost in a shell - What the heck is a Terminal,Shell and TTY.png" type="image/png" length="61065" /> </item> <item> <title>Rise of Internal Developer Portals (iDp) - Part 1</title> <category>Engineering</category> <category>topic/devops</category> <category>topic/platform-engineering</category> <description>&lt;h1&gt;Rise of Internal Developer Portals (iDp) - Part 1&lt;/h1&gt;&lt;p&gt;In today&#39;s rapidly evolving software development landscape, staying ahead of the curve is crucial for success. One emerging trend that has gained significant traction is the adoption of Internal Developer Portals (iDp). &lt;/p&gt;</description><link>https://blog.shaishav.kr/2024/04/18/rise-of-internal-developer-portals-idp---part-1/?utm_source=documentation&amp;utm_medium=RSS&amp;utm_campaign=feed-syndication</link> <pubDate>Tue, 23 Jul 2024 20:37:31 +0000</pubDate><source url="https://blog.shaishav.kr/feed_rss_created.xml">wiresurfer's library | © shaishav.kr</source><guid isPermaLink="true">https://blog.shaishav.kr/2024/04/18/rise-of-internal-developer-portals-idp---part-1/</guid> <enclosure url="https://blog.shaishav.kr/assets/images/social/Articles/2024/April/Rise of Internal Developer Portals (iDp) - Part 1.png" type="image/png" length="59539" /> </item> <item> <title>Story Untold is a Story Lost</title> <category>Insights</category> <category>topic/personal-development</category> <category>topic/writing</category> <description>Have you ever felt that you aren&#39;t valued in this world. Do you feel people dont &#34;see&#34; you? Have you asked yourself the question, do you tell your story?</description><link>https://blog.shaishav.kr/2024/07/22/story-untold-is-a-story-lost/?utm_source=documentation&amp;utm_medium=RSS&amp;utm_campaign=feed-syndication</link> <pubDate>Tue, 23 Jul 2024 20:37:31 +0000</pubDate><source url="https://blog.shaishav.kr/feed_rss_created.xml">wiresurfer's library | © shaishav.kr</source><guid isPermaLink="true">https://blog.shaishav.kr/2024/07/22/story-untold-is-a-story-lost/</guid> <enclosure url="https://blog.shaishav.kr/assets/images/social/Articles/2024/July/Story untold is a story lost.png" type="image/png" length="52215" /> </item> <item> <title>Tech Tip - Getting QT5 to respect system wide dark mode and GTK theme</title> <category>Engineering</category> <category>topic/linux</category> <category>topic/qt5</category> <category>topic/tech-tips</category> <description>It seems my quest for a low overhead xubuntu desktop comes with its fair share of small annoying little gremlins. Today we talk about how QT5 and Ubuntu sometimes don&#39;t play nice specially when it comes to respecting dark mode themes. I will go throuh my motivations to use xubutu, or rather any operating system image for that matter.</description><link>https://blog.shaishav.kr/2024/07/22/tech-tip---getting-qt5-to-respect-system-wide-dark-mode-and-gtk-theme/?utm_source=documentation&amp;utm_medium=RSS&amp;utm_campaign=feed-syndication</link> <pubDate>Tue, 23 Jul 2024 20:37:31 +0000</pubDate><source url="https://blog.shaishav.kr/feed_rss_created.xml">wiresurfer's library | © shaishav.kr</source><guid isPermaLink="true">https://blog.shaishav.kr/2024/07/22/tech-tip---getting-qt5-to-respect-system-wide-dark-mode-and-gtk-theme/</guid> <enclosure url="https://blog.shaishav.kr/assets/images/social/Articles/2024/July/Tech Tip - Getting QT5 to respect system wide dark mode and GTK theme.png" type="image/png" length="66973" /> </item> <item> <title>Visual Programming - Promised Utopia and the Advent of GenAI</title> <category>Engineering</category> <category>topic/GenAI</category> <category>topic/software-development</category> <category>topic/visual-programming</category> <description>&lt;h1&gt;Visual Programming - Promised Utopia and the Advent of GenAI&lt;/h1&gt;&lt;p&gt;Visual programming has long been heralded as the future of software development, promising a utopia where coding is as intuitive as drawing. The allure lies in its potential to make programming accessible to non-coders, streamline workflows, and enhance productivity through a more visual, interactive approach. However, despite its potential, visual programming has not seen massive adoption. In this article, we will explore the history of visual programming, analyze why it has struggled to gain traction, and discuss how Generative AI (GenAI) is poised to revolutionize this field.&lt;/p&gt;</description><link>https://blog.shaishav.kr/2024/07/15/visual-programming---promised-utopia-and-the-advent-of-genai/?utm_source=documentation&amp;utm_medium=RSS&amp;utm_campaign=feed-syndication</link> <pubDate>Tue, 23 Jul 2024 20:37:31 +0000</pubDate><source url="https://blog.shaishav.kr/feed_rss_created.xml">wiresurfer's library | © shaishav.kr</source><guid isPermaLink="true">https://blog.shaishav.kr/2024/07/15/visual-programming---promised-utopia-and-the-advent-of-genai/</guid> <enclosure url="https://blog.shaishav.kr/assets/images/social/Articles/2024/July/Visual Programming - Promised Utopia and the Advent of GenAI.png" type="image/png" length="55289" /> </item> <item> <title>Unleash the Forbidden - Enabling eBPF/XDP for Kernel Tinkering on WSL2</title> <category>Engineering</category> <category>topic/platform-engineering</category> <description>We&#39;ll focus on enabling eBPF on Ubuntu 20.04 running on WSL2. You can try it on 18.04, but your mileage may vary. Here’s a high-level overview of what we’ll do:1. Recompile the WSL2 kernel with specific eBPF-related flags enabled.2. Change the WSL2 configuration in Windows to point to our newly compiled kernel.3. Restart WSL2.4. Verify the new kernel is running and eBPF is enabled.</description><link>https://blog.shaishav.kr/2024/06/04/unleash-the-forbidden---enabling-ebpfxdp-for-kernel-tinkering-on-wsl2/?utm_source=documentation&amp;utm_medium=RSS&amp;utm_campaign=feed-syndication</link> <pubDate>Tue, 23 Jul 2024 20:37:31 +0000</pubDate><source url="https://blog.shaishav.kr/feed_rss_created.xml">wiresurfer's library | © shaishav.kr</source><guid isPermaLink="true">https://blog.shaishav.kr/2024/06/04/unleash-the-forbidden---enabling-ebpfxdp-for-kernel-tinkering-on-wsl2/</guid> <enclosure url="https://blog.shaishav.kr/assets/images/social/Articles/2024/Jun/Unleash the Forbidden - Enabling eBPFXDP for Kernel Tinkering on WSL2.png" type="image/png" length="62260" /> </item> </channel></rss>